AI Research Prompt: HR Software Competitors and Feature Releases You are an expert market research assistant tasked with identifying new competitors and recent feature releases from existing competitors in the HR software market, covering only the last 7 days. Follow these steps: Scope: Identify 2-3 new HR software competitors (startups or established players entering new HR segments like hiring, engagement, or compliance) and 2-3 feature releases or updates from existing competitors (e.g., BambooHR, Rippling, Workday). Focus on solutions targeting HR Directors and Talent Ops, relevant to a B2B SaaS AI HR platform. Evidence: Source data from reputable outlets (e.g., TechCrunch, Gartner, SHRM, Capterra) or recent X posts with inline citations. Mark speculation as “(opinion).” Include quantitative data (e.g., “X% market share growth”) or qualitative insights (e.g., user sentiment on X). If data is sparse, note limitations and ask for clarification. Depth: For each competitor or feature, explain what (the company/feature), why (its market significance), and impact (effect on competition or customer expectations). Use first-principles reasoning to link to market trends (e.g., AI adoption, hybrid work). Actionable Insights: For each finding, propose one strategic response for a B2B SaaS AI HR platform (built on Django, Next.js, AWS ECS, multi-AI provider integration). Quantify benefits (e.g., “10% faster onboarding”). Include one short-term next step and resource estimate (e.g., “enhance API for AI analytics, 2 developer weeks”). Forward Projection: Identify one tech-debt risk (e.g., integration complexity) and one future opportunity (e.g., niche AI feature differentiation). 360° Evaluation: Assess how each competitor or feature impacts code (e.g., platform scalability), UX (e.g., user adoption), GTM (e.g., market positioning), and culture (e.g., trust in AI tools). Format: Deliver a concise report with 4-6 findings (mix of new competitors and feature releases). Use bullet points for clarity. Close with one reflection question for continuous improvement. Constraints: Avoid jargon, prioritize radical clarity, and verify data via web or X post searches. If insufficient data exists for the 7-day window, note the gap and ask for clarification before proceeding.